 Spartans hunted and killed Helots (Sparta's serfs) as an initiation rite, and where Aristotle and other philosophers helped to justify raids to capture and enslave foreigners by creating the concept of natural slaves. He discusses the hunt for heretics in the Middle Ages; New World natives in the early modern period; vagrants, Jews, criminals, and runaway slaves in other eras; and illegal immigrants today. Exploring evolving ideas about the human and the subhuman, what we owe to enemies and people on the margins of society, and the supposed legitimacy of domination, Chamayou shows that the hunting of humans should not be treated ahistorically, and that manhunting has varied as widely in its justifications and aims as in its practices. He investigates the psychology of manhunting, noting that many people, from bounty hunters to Balzac, have written about the thrill of hunting when the prey is equally intelligent and cunning. An unconventional history on an unconventional subject, Manhunts is an in-depth consideration of the dynamics of an age-old form of violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aHuntingxPhilosophy. 0aLynching. 0aMinoritiesxCrimes against. 0aViolencexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican slavery.  aAfricans.  aAmerican Indians.  aChristian pastoralism.  aGreeks.  aIndian hunting.  aJews.  aNew World.  aNimrod.  aRen Girard.  aWestern capitalism.  aacquisition hunts.  aacquisition.  aancient Greece.  aanti-Semitism.  aauthority.  abegging.  ablacks.  acapture.  acollective mobilization.  aconquest.  acynegetic power.  acynegetic powers.  adomination.  aenslavement.  aexclusion.  aextermination hunts.  aforeign workers.  aforeigners.  aheretics.  ahunted.  ahunter.  ahunting.  aillegal aliens